One convenient way is to view it as a geometric‐series of ratio –1/3.  For example,

\[
-\tfrac13+\tfrac19-\tfrac1{27}+\tfrac1{81}-\tfrac1{243}
\;=\;\sum_{n=1}^{5}\Bigl(-\tfrac13\Bigr)^{n}
\;=\;\sum_{n=1}^{5}\frac{(-1)^{n}}{3^{n}}\,.
\]

This is a geometric series with first term \(a=49\) and common ratio  
\[r=\frac{7}{49}=\frac17,\]  
and since \(|r|<1\) the infinite sum is  
\[
S=\frac{a}{1-r}
=\frac{49}{1-\frac17}
=\frac{49}{\frac67}
=\frac{49\cdot7}{6}
=\frac{343}{6}.
\]
